full_title: I Look in People's Windows by Taylor Swift
title: I Look in People’s Windows

description.plain:
“I Look in People’s Windows” is the twenty-fifth track off THE TORTURED POETS DEPARTMENT: THE ANTHOLOGY and the ninth bonus track on the album, which was surprise released at 2am, two hours after the original THE TORTURED POETS DEPARTMENT release.

Lyrically, Taylor Swift explores the aftermath of a lost connection, reminiscing about fleeting moments and yearning for what could have been. Swift portrays the bitter-sweetness of observing others' lives, imagining scenarios where they might cross paths, capturing the ache of longing for lost connections and the quiet desperation of seeking closure.

The track samples her own track in 2019’s “Death By A Thousand Cuts,” expressing the completely different emotion from looking in a window to see her lover to finding her lover through people’s windows if he was still there:

I look through the windows of this love
Even though we boarded them up

The title and the premise of the song could be referring to Emily Dickinson’s I had been hungry, all the Years, in which the persona talks about a life of being outside a house and looking in through a window, which symbolizes a longing for connection.

Swift herself was recently revealed to be distantly related to Dickinson, and has previously mentioned:

If my lyrics sound like a letter written by Emily Dickinson’s great-grandmother while sewing a lace curtain, that’s me writing in the quill genre.

I had died the tiniest death
I spied the catch in your breath
Out, out, out, out, out, out
Northbound I got carried away
As you boarded your train
South, south, south, south, south, south

A feather taken by the wind blowing
I'm afflicted by the not knowing, so

I look in people's windows
Transfixed by rose golden glows
They have their friends over to drink nice wine
I look in people's windows
In case you're at their table
What if your eyes looked up and met mine
One more time?

You had stopped and tiltеd your head
I still ponder what it meant
Now, now, now, now, now, now
I triеd searching faces on streets
What are the chances you'd be
Downtown, downtown, downtown

Does it feel alright to not know me?
I'm addicted to the "if only"

So I look in people's windows
Like I'm some deranged weirdo
I attend Christmas parties from outside
I look in people's windows
In case you're at their table
What if your eyes looked up and met mine
One more time?
